ble-content"><div dir=3D"auto" class=3D"body markup"><p>Some topics I discu=
ss in this third installment of Rob Henderson=E2=80=99s Office Hours:</p><d=
iv class=3D"paywall-jump" data-component-name=3D"PaywallToDOM"></div><ul><l=
i><p><span>There=E2=80=99s a viral story about some guy named Harry Sisson =
who convinced 11 women to send him nudes. Predictably, reactions are split =
along gender lines. It=E2=80=99s reminding me of the West Elm Caleb drama a=
nd last year=E2=80=99s </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/an=
drew-hubermans-5-body-problem" rel=3D"">Andrew Huberman saga</a><span>.</sp=
an></p></li><li><p>A lot of guys are defending this guy using evolutionary =
logic=E2=80=94"men are wired to sleep around"=E2=80=94but conveniently igno=
ring that evolution also favors women shaming men for it.</p></li><li><p>Sp=
eaking of evolutionary logic, every few months, Leonardo DiCaprio trends fo=
r dating a different young woman. And every time, men defend him while wome=
n roll their eyes. But both reactions make perfect evolutionary sense.</p><=
/li></ul><ul><li><p>Daniel Kahneman, the Nobel-winning psychologist, chose =
assisted suicide last year at age 90=E2=80=94he made a calculated decision =
to exit on his own terms.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Annie Duke, the professio=
nal poker player-turned-psychologist, has this great line: "Quitting on tim=
e feels like quitting too early." Did Kahneman =E2=80=9Cquit=E2=80=9D at th=
e right moment? The ethics of assisted suicide come with a weird paradox=E2=
=80=94if you=E2=80=99re mentally sharp, it feels too soon. But if you=E2=80=
=99re in decline, people say you=E2=80=99re not competent enough to choose.=
 Where=E2=80=99s the line?</p></li></ul><ul><li><p><span>Revisiting </span>=
<em>Thinking, Fast and Slow</em><span>=E2=80=94one of the most influential =
books on human psychology=E2=80=94and reflecting on how we default to perso=
nal anecdotes over statistics. Kahneman=E2=80=99s "planning fallacy" is a p=
erfect example: we always think we are the exception=E2=80=94when the data =
suggests otherwise.</span></p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Recapping my recent book=
 event with Dr. Drew at the Manhattan Institute=E2=80=94if you had told 17-=
year-old me I=E2=80=99d be sharing a stage with him, that to me would have =
been the equivalent of you telling me I=E2=80=99d be the first astronaut on=
 Mars. Surreal. If you missed the event we did, don=E2=80=99t worry=E2=80=
=94the recording is coming soon.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Growing up, the ra=
dio show Loveline was one of the few positive influences in my life. Dr. Dr=
ew spent years speaking with troubled teens on the air, so when he read my =
book, he got it instantly. </p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Why shorter public talk=
s require more preparation than longer talks.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Discu=
ssing whether books are =E2=80=9Coutdated,=E2=80=9D as I recently heard a t=
ech executive declare at a conference.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Some say ign=
oring the news is a luxury, but the data says otherwise: the wealthiest and=
 most educated consume the most political news.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>The=
 most surprising political shift of 2024. Overall, white voters didn't shif=
t at all in their voting preferences from 2016 to 2024, while nonwhite vote=
rs all shifted to the Republican side.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Recently att=
ended a conference where a mainstream media reporter gave the most honest b=
reakdown of why Democrats lost. I share my thoughts on his explanation.</p>=
</li></ul><ul><li><p>Explaining why I have no current plans to launch a pod=
cast</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>Some thoughts on imposter syndrome, and why it=
=E2=80=99s most common in intellectual and creative fields</p></li></ul><ul=
><li><p>If you knew a book was half-written by AI, would you still want to =
read it? I wouldn=E2=80=99t.</p></li></ul><ul><li><p>How classical liberals=
 became =E2=80=9Cright-wing=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 you can be a lifelong libera=
l who has never voted for a Republican in your life, but in academia, if yo=
u support free speech and challenge identity politics, you get labeled a co=
nservative.</p></li></ul><p>Join me for my next live video in the app.</p><=
